article.headline: Iowa State 69, California Riverside 61
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Mike Taylor scored 22 points and Iowa State rebounded from a shaky stretch at the end of the first half to give Greg McDermott a victory in his first game as coach, 69-61 over UC Riverside on Friday night. Freshman Wesley Johnson added 10 points for the Cyclones, who finally took control midway through the second half after trailing by three at halftime against a team that was 5-23 last season. B.J. Visman led UC Riverside in the season-opening Cyclone Challenge with 17 points and Larry Cunningham scored 12. There were 45 turnovers in the ragged game -- 23 by UC Riverside. McDermott succeeded Wayne Morgan at Iowa State after five seasons at Northern Iowa, the last three ending with NCAA tournament appearances. Only four scholarship players returned after Morgan was fired and one, 6-foot-11 Jiri Hubalek, is ineligible for the first six games because of NCAA rules violations. That forced McDermott to scramble to assemble a team and he ended up with four freshmen and two junior-college transfers in his rotation. The inexperience showed at times, especially after Iowa State jumped to an early 11-point lead. With the Cyclones forcing quick shots and turning it over, UC Riverside went on a 19-6 run that Visman finished with a turnaround shot that gave the Highlanders a 33-30 lead. Iowa State had the final possession of the half after forcing a shot clock violation, but Taylor, a junior-college transfer, lost the ball while working for a shot. When the buzzer sounded seconds later, McDermott went onto the court to talk to Taylor, put an arm around him and continued talking as they walked to the dressing room. The Cyclones regained the lead by going 7-for-10 on free throws in the first 7 minutes of the second half before pulling away behind Johnson and Rahshon Clark, the team's top returning scorer. Each scored on a tip-in and a nifty turnaround shot inside to spark an 11-2 run that stretched the lead to 51-41. Johnson's three-point play off another turnaround made it 55-41 and Clark topped off the victory with a sweeping follow-up dunk that made it 65-57 with 1:10 remaining. Clark finished with nine points. After its miserable 2005-06 season, UC Riverside endured a stressful preseason. Sophomore forward Mark Hall was killed and three teammates were injured in a traffic accident in September, then coach David Spencer took a medical leave of absence. Assistant Vonn Webb is interim coach.
